:"1436–1495","1443–1495":"1443–1495","1460–1505":"1460–1505","1462–Male":"1462–Deceased","1483–1536":"1483–1536","1404–1483":"1404–1483","1420–1440":"1420–1440","1440":"1440","1495":"1495","1462":"1462","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1404":"1404","1536":"1536","1436":"1436","26 May 1483":"26 May 1483","1443":"1443","26 August 1495":"26 August 1495","1420":"1420","ABT. 1435":"about 1435","about 1462":"about 1462","1505":"1505","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Sanquhar Castle, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Terregles, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Terregles, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Terregles, Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland":"Terregles, Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Herries","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, Scottish, English: locative name from Hérils in Trévières (Calvados). The name in England may have died out before the end of the medieval period, but survived into the modern period in Scotland.","2  English: variant of   Herry   with genitival or post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>.  Compare  Harris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Herris","meanings":["English:  see  Herries  ."]},{"name":"Herry","meanings":["Scots: Herry, to plunder, most properly to plunder birds' nests"]},{"name":"Harris","meanings":["English (southern England and south Wales): from the personal name   Harry   + genitival <i>-s</i>. This surname is also established in Ireland, taken there principally during the Plantation of Ulster. However, in some cases, particularly in families coming from County Mayo, <i>Harris</i> can be an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarchadha</b>. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","American shortened and altered form of Greek surnames begining with <i>Cha(r)-</i>, such as <b>Chasandrinos</b> (variant of <b>Kassandrinos</b>, a habitational name from the Kassandra peninsula of Chalkidiki), and various patronymics from the personal name <i>Charalampos</i> (see   Charos  ). In North America, the surname <i>Harris</i> may possibly also originate from a transferred use of the Greek personal (given) name <i>Charis</i> or <i>Harris</i> (shortened forms of <i>Charalampos</i>) as a surname (i.e. as a replacement of the original surname).","Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord David Herries 5th Lord Of Terregles was born in 1436, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Herries, was 32 and his mother, Elizabeth McClellan, was 16. He had at least 3 sons with Lady Margaret Crichton. He died on 26 August 1495, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1436–26 August 1495":"1436–26. august 1495","1436–1495":"1436–1495","1443–1495":"1443–1495","1460–1505":"1460–1505","1462–Male":"1